          "body": "David's petition against the enemy begins with a Babel-echo: 'Confuse, O Lord, divide their tongues' (55:9). The prayer evokes Genesis 11:7-9 — the scattering of coordinated wickedness by linguistic division. The conspiracy against David depends on unified counsel (Ahithophel's advice was 'like consulting the oracle of God,' 2 Samuel 16:23), and David prays that unity apart. What follows in verses 10-11 is a portrait of Jerusalem as a city whose infrastructure of order — walls, streets, interior life — has become the infrastructure of wickedness: violence, strife, iniquity, mischief, destruction, oppression, and deceit named in sequence. Then the pivot of verses 12-14, the psalm's most painful lines: 'But it is you, a man my equal, my companion and my familiar friend; we who had sweet fellowship together, walked in the house of God in the throng.' The betrayal is triply devastating — equal standing (no power differential to explain it), shared intimacy (the inner ring of *sod*, 55:14), and shared worship (walking together in God's house). Spurgeon called this verse 'the sharpest arrow in the quiver of grief — not the enemy's dart but the friend's.' The imprecation of verse 15 (let them go down alive to Sheol) must be read as covenantal justice language, not personal revenge fantasy. The evil that dwells within the betrayer (55:15) is the same *qerev*-interior evil that infests the city (55:10-11) — systemic, not merely individual."
